The Literary Magic of Harry Potter
Princeton —— This summer, readers around the world held celebrations marking the 20th anniversary of the first book in J.K. Rowling's Harry Potter series —— Harry Potter and the Sorcerer’s Stone (renamed Harry Potter and the Philosopher's Stone in the United States). They had ample reason to celebrate.
Since the young wizard first appeared on June 26, 1997, this "Boy Who Lived" has become a symbol of resilience and perseverance.
Over the past 20 years, the Harry Potter series has expanded to include seven novels, translated into over 70 languages, and has sold a combined total of 450 million copies.
The eight movies based on this book have earned a cumulative $7 billion, while Harry Potter-themed toys and merchandise have generated an additional $7 billion in revenue.
It is hard to imagine a day when global audiences were not captivated by Rowling's works for those of specific age groups and with literary sensibilities.
Therefore, I am always amazed when I recall my students' poor reaction to the book Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone in the fall of 1999, when I included it in the syllabus for my popular literature course at Princeton University. I have been teaching a course on "Bestselling Books in America" since 1993.
This course examines popular works from the 17th century to the present, inviting students to reflect on why and how these bestselling works have attracted their audiences.
At the end of every semester, I ask students to choose a final book that represents the popular taste.
In 1999, they chose the first Harry Potter novel.
That year, the Potter mania hit the American coast猛烈地。
In June, the American publisher of the series urgently pushed the hardcover edition of the second book in the series, Harry Potter and the Chamber of Secrets, into bookstores.
The publisher also released the third book in the series, Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban, on September 8, as well as the paperback edition of Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone.
By the end of the month, Rowling's novels had taken the top three spots on the New York Times Best Seller list, with the paperback edition of Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone claiming the number one spot on the paperback bestseller list.
Time magazine even put this glasses-wearing wizard on its cover.
The image of Harry Potter is everywhere in sight.
My students were eager to know why such a frenzy was happening.
Oh my goodness, they were completely disappointed.
In their eyes, the Harry Potter series was nothing more than second-rate nonsense, far from the cherished series like The Chronicles of Narnia or The Lord of the Rings from their childhood memories.
Although their childhood had only just passed a few years ago, they criticized Harry Potter, just like many notorious adult critics: "Made up," "Poor writing," "Clichéd," and "Boring."

In their eyes, Harry had neither miracles, nor intelligence, nor warmth.
The students' aversion surprised me, but in retrospect, it was not anything to be overly surprised about.
Although adults have always formed a large part of the audience for Harry Potter, these students were exactly in the wrong age group to objectively understand the Harry Potter phenomenon.
They had already passed the age of accepting new children's books, but at the same time were too young to have their own children (I had just had my own child at the time), and they were eager to insist that although the Harry Potter series was now very popular, it would soon be forgotten.
In the fall of the next year, that is, 2000, the next batch of students also chose Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone as the final book for analysis, just like their predecessors, confidently refusing to accept the work.
Let's fast forward to spring of 2007.
After putting the course on hold for several years, I taught "Bestselling Books in America" again.
When the students chose the final book for analysis, they chose Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone.
And I was ready to face their criticism.
But this time, their comments were very positive.
This was a new generation of students, born between 1986 and 1989, who were not college students when they first read Rowling's works, but rather teenagers in their early teens, just beginning to enter adolescence. This meant they grew up into young adulthood alongside Harry, Ron, and Hermione.
The same thing happened again in the fall of 2010.
For these students, "We grew up with Harry Potter" had become a motto, not just a label.
Would Harry ever fade from memory?
We will never be able to forget it as long as we are alive.
Since 2010, I have taught the bestselling books course twice, and in both instances, the students chose non-Harry Potter novels for their final critiques.
Are they tired of Potter?
This seems unlikely based on the reviews received for the Potter series in my other course on "Children's Literature," where I taught Rowling's works.
Now, I have chosen to include a Harry Potter novel in the syllabus, but I did not choose "Harry Potter and the Sorcerer's Stone," but rather "Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban" — this is my favorite of the seven Harry Potter novels, and it marks the transition of the series from children's literature to young adult fiction, with complex portrayals of loyalty, betrayal, anger, and compassion.
Many of my students also love this book the most.
How long can the popularity of the Harry Potter series last?
Every time I teach children's literature, I start with a survey: "Which books from the list did you read as a child?"
In 2010, 86% of people had read "Harry Potter and the Prisoner of Azkaban."
In 2012, this number rose to 94%.
But in the years that followed, the percentage continued to decline — in 2014 it was 87%, and by 2016 it had dropped to 81%.
These are not scientific figures, I know.
But I am curious: will the percentage of students who have read Harry Potter drop below 80% next spring when I teach "Children's Literature" again?
Will the facts prove that the students from 1999 to 2000 were right, that Harry Potter's status is continuously declining and will never become an eternal classic?
Or is there a balance point ahead where the percentage can remain stable and no longer decline?
Perhaps Harry's 40th anniversary will tell us the answer.
Until then, I am happy to invite him into my classroom.
